{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> φρήν</b>, ἡ, <br /> <i>genitive</i> φρενός, <i>plural</i> φρένες, <i>genitive</i> φρενῶν, <i>dative</i> φρεσί: older <i>dative</i> <i>plural</i> φρασί (ν) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “IG” 12.971 (6th c.BC), 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 3.62, “BMus.Inscription” 909 (Halic., 1st c.BC): (see. entry near the end)\">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]: <br /><Level2><b>__I</b></Level2> <b>midriff,</b> κραδία φρένα λακτίζει [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 881 (_anapaest meter_)\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; elsewhere always in <i>plural</i>, ἔνθα φρένες ἔρχαται ἀμφ᾽ ἁδινὸν κῆρ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 16.481, compare 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ ἀρχαίης ἰητρικῇς” 22, “Art.” 41 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; τὰς φρένας διάφραγμα εἰς τὸ μέσον αὐτῶν (i.e. τοῦ θώρακος καὶ τοῦ κύτους) τιθέντες [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Timaeus” 70a; τοῦτο δὲ τὸ διάζωμα καλοῦσί τινες φρένας, ὃ διορίζει τόν τε πλεύμονα καὶ τὴν καρδίαν 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “de Partibus Animalium” 672b11, compare “HA” 496b11, 506a6; also, in 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus, more vaguely, πρὸς στῆθος ὅθι φρένες ἧπαρ ἔχουσι 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 9.301; μένεος φρένες ἀμφὶ μέλαιναι πίμπλαντ᾽ 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.103, +others; φρένας.. εἰς αὐτὰς τυπείς 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 363, compare “Eu.” 159 (Lyric poetry). \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__I.2</b></Level3> <b>heart,</b> as seat of the passions, e.g. of fear, τρομέοντο δέ οἱ φρένες ἐντός [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 10.10 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of joy and grief, φρένα τέρπεσθαι φόρμιγγι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 9.186; γάνυται φρένα ποιμήν 13.493; τί σε φρένας ἵκετοπένθο; 1.362; ἄχος πύκασε φρένας 8.124; ἔρως φρένας ἀμφεκάλυψε 3.442 \">Refs</a>]; of anger, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 6.147 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of courage, ἕνα φρεσὶ θυμὸν ἔχοντες [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 13.487; ἐς φρένα θυμὸς ἀγέρθη 22.475, compare 8.202 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], etc.; of bodily appetites, such as hunger, etc., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 11.89 \">Refs</a>]: the shades of the dead are without it, ψυχὴ καὶ εἴδωλον, ἀτὰρ φρένες οὐκ ἔνι πάμπαν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 23.104 \">Refs</a>] (except the shade of Teiresias, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 10.493)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: so generally in Poets, φρενὸς ἔνδοθεν ἄλγεα κεῖται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.BC: Solon Lyricus cited in 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Ἀθηναίων Πολιτεία” 5.2; κῆλα δαιμόνων θέλγει φρένας 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 1.12; φόβος μ᾽ ἔχει φρένας 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 379; μαινομένα φρενί [prev. author] “Th.” 484 (Lyric poetry); στυγεῖν μιᾷ φρενί [prev. author] “Eu.” 986 (Lyric poetry); Διὸς γὰρ δυσπαραίτητοι φ. [prev. author] “Pr.” 34 \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]; ἐκ φρενός from one's <b>very heart,</b> ὁ ἐκ φρενὸς λόγος a <b>sincere</b> speech, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Ch.” 107; ἐτύμως δακρυχέων ἐκ φρενός [prev. author] “Th.” 919 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs</a>]; οὐκ ἀπ᾽ ἄκρας φρενός not <b>superficially and carelessly,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Ag.” 805 (_anapaest meter_); φρενὸς ἐκ φιλίας [prev. work] 1515 (_anapaest meter_), compare 546 \">Refs</a>]; φῦσαι φρένας to produce <b>a haughty spirit,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 1463. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__I.3</b></Level3> <b>mind,</b> as seat of the mental faculties, perception, thought, ἔγνω ᾗσιν ἐνὶ φ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 22.296; μή μοι ταῦτα νόει φρεσί 9.600 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; μετὰ φρεσὶ μερμηρίξαι, βάλλεσθαι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 10.438, 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.434; ἴδμεν ἐνὶ φρεσίν 2.301 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; τῷ γὰρ ἐπὶ φρεσί θῆκε put in his <b>mind, suggested</b> it,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1.55; σφῶϊν δ᾽ ὧδε θεῶν τις ἐνὶ φρεσὶ ποιήσειεν 13.55; ἐν φρεσὶ θέσθε ἕκαστος [prev. work] 121, compare 1.297, etc.; φρένας παραπεῖσαι, πείθειν, 7.120, 16.842 \">Refs</a>]; ἐπιγνάμπτει φρένας (variant for{νόον}) ἐσθλῶν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 9.514; Διὸς ἐτράπετο φρήν 10.45 \">Refs</a>]; ἀνὴρ φρένας ἀφνειός rich (only) <b>in his imagination,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 455 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὀρθᾷ, ἐλευθέρᾳ φρενί, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 8.24, “P.” 2.57; φρένες γὰρ αὐτοῦ θυμὸν ᾠακοστρόφουν 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Persae” 767; ἡ γλῶσσ᾽ ὀμώμοχ᾽, ἡ δὲ φ. ἀνώμοτος 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 612; κατὰ φρένα καὶ κατὰ θυμόν 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.193, +others\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>plural</i>, <b>wits,</b> Κύκλωπα περὶ φρένας ἤλυθε οἶνος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 9.362, compare 454, 18.331; πλήγη φρένας ἂς πάρος εἶχεν 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 13.394; ἐκ γὰρ πλήγη φρένας 16.403; βλάπτε φρένας Ζεὺς ἡμετέρας 15.724; ἐξ... τοι θεοὶ φρένας ὤλεσαν 7.360; φρένας ἄφρων, φρένας ἠλέ or ἠλεέ, 4.104, 15.128, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 2.243 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: of losing one's <b>wits,</b> φρενῶν ἀφεστάναι, ἐκστῆναι, μεθεστάναι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 865, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Orestes” 1021, “Ba.” 944; τὰς φ. ἐκβάλλειν 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 648; ἔξω φρενῶν 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 7.47; φρενῶν οὐκ ἔνδον ὤν 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Heraclidae” 709; φρενῶν κεκομμένος 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 479 (Lyric poetry); κενός 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 754; τητώμενοι [prev. author] “El.” 1326 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἔξεδροι, παράκοποι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 935, “Ba.” 33; ποῦ ποτ᾽ εἶ φρενῶ; 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 390; φρένες διάστροφοι 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 673, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 447; μαργότης φρενῶν [prev. author] “fragment” 846; ἀνακίνησις φρενῶν [prev. author] “OT” 727, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of persons in their senses, ἐπήβολος φρενῶν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Ant.” 492; ἀνδρὸς νοῦν ἔχοντος καὶ φρένας 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ranae” 535 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] (so in later Prose, οἱ φρένας ἔχοντες [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Philodemus Philosophus “περὶ ποιημάτων” 5.19, “Rh.” 1.240S.; οἱ τῶν σοφιστῶν τὰς κοινὰς φ. ἔχοντες [prev. work]202S.); also ἔσω φρενῶν λέγειν 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1052; γράφου φρενῶν ἔσω 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 1325; τῆς λεπτότητος τῶν φ. 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 153 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; φρένες, opposed to σῶμα, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.134; so αἱ σάρκες αἱ κεναὶ φρενῶν 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Electra” 387 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; attributed to animals, μετὰ φρεσὶ γίγνεται ἀλκή [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 4.245, compare 16.157, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]—The word is not common in early Prose, τίς αὐτῶν νόος ἢ φρή; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.AD(?): Heraclitus 104 \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]; συμφορὰ τῶν φ., i.e. madness, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 2.7; παραλλάττει τῶν φ. 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator “Fragmenta” 90; καρποῦ μὲν ἀφθονία φρενῶν δὲ ἀφορία 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Symposium” 4.55; νοῦς καὶ φρένες 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 18.324, compare 25.33. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__I.4</b></Level3> <b>will, purpose,</b> οὔ τι Διὸς βέομαι φρεσίν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.194; σῆς ἀπεστάτουν φ. 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 993, compare “OC” 1182 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>].—In usage there is little or no distinction observable between <i>singular</i> and <i>plural</i>, but the <i>singular</i> is not found in Prose (except [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.AD(?): Heraclitus [same place]) or Comedy texts (except in _paratragoedia_, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ranae” 886). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G5424","accentedUnicode":"φρήν","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G5426","matchingForm":"φρονέω","stepTransliteration":"froneō","gloss":"to reason","_zh_tw_Gloss":"思念, 守, 意念","_es_Gloss":"pensar","_zh_Gloss":"思念, 守, 意念"},{"strongNumber":"G5429","matchingForm":"φρόνιμος","stepTransliteration":"fronimos","gloss":"thoughtful","_zh_tw_Gloss":"聰明, 有見識","_es_Gloss":"prudente","_zh_Gloss":"聪明, 有见识"},{"strongNumber":"G5431","matchingForm":"φροντίζω","stepTransliteration":"frontizō","gloss":"be careful","_zh_tw_Gloss":"留心","_es_Gloss":"tener cuidado","_zh_Gloss":"留心"}],"shortDef":"(<i>plural</i>) thinking, understanding","mediumDef":"(<i>plural</i>) thinking, understanding <br /><i>primarily</i> <b>the diaphragm, midriff; the mind, intellect, understanding,</b> <ref='1Co.14.20'>1Cor. 14:20</ref> (2x)*","stepGloss":"thinking","stepTransliteration":"frēn","count":2,"_es_Definition":"manera de pensar, pensamiento, comprensión, raciocinio","_zh_tw_Definition":"(仔細考量) 思考, 理解 (林前 14:20)","_zh_Definition":"(仔细考量) 思考, 理解 (林前 14:20)","_step_Type":"word","_vi_Definition":"sự trí tuệ sự hiểu biết; lý luận; ý thức","_zh_tw_Gloss":"心志上","_es_Gloss":"modo de pensar","_zh_Gloss":"心志上"}]}